(358, 64, 0, 1, '2018-03-09 18:16:33', '2018-03-09 14:17:49', 50, 'ge', 1, 1, 'Charity (GE)', 'Char', NULL, '<p><img style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" src="/files/sponsors/charity-logo.png" alt="autism.ge" width="124" height="129" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Beyond athletic achievement, your participation in the Great Batumi Night Race will give you the additional satisfaction of supporting the &ldquo;We are Others! (Seeing Differently)&rdquo; Charity Foundation, which was founded in 2016 by Andrei and Alexandra Maximov to support children and adults with Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD). 30% of the marathon registration fees will be donated to the foundation, which will use the funds to finance its projects in 2018. The foundation was chosen as the beneficiary for charitable donations in order to facilitate the foundation&rsquo;s successful implementation of new projects, build on the success of previous efforts, and guarantee full financial transparency.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>SLOGANS: We are different, try to understand us! Autism isn&rsquo;t a tragedy; ignorance is a tragedy!</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>LOGO: The Foundation logo is a jigsaw puzzle piece in the form of a blue butterfly. &nbsp;The butterfly comes from the caterpillar and symbolizes an ability for transformation.&nbsp; For many people, the color blue symbolizes innocence and a child&rsquo;s wonder and content.&nbsp; Finally, the jigsaw puzzle piece itself consists of four small human figure, two adults and two children.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>MISSION: To accelerate the adoption in Georgia of a system, already in place in developed countries, &nbsp;that cares and supports children and adults with ASD. To implement best practices in ASD therapy and education based on the experience, achievements, and expertize of the top international experts who truly understand how to achieve progress in helping these &ldquo;different&rdquo; people with special needs.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>GOALS &ndash; Our goals are as ambitious as they are achievable</p>\n<p>​</p>\n<ol>\n<li>To change attitudes towards children and adults with ASD in Georgia by addressing:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>The Georgian state: Delivering and proving the thesis that an investment of 100 lari into the rehabilitation and social adaptation of an ASD child and/or adult will save 1000 lari in future welfare costs;</li>\n<li>Georgian society: Explaining that ASD is not a disability; People with ASD may seem different, but society must understand and adapt to their follow citizens; &nbsp;</li>\n<li>The professional medical and educational community: Persuading specialists that each child with ASD has their own individual path for rehabilitation and that a panacea or universal rehabilitation plan does not exist; &nbsp;</li>\n<li>Parents: Explaining that they can not rely only on the work of specialists for success, but that they should be prepared to understand what is going on with their child, what he or she needs, and how to supplement the specialists&rsquo; treatment with their own efforts.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol start="2">\n<li>To deliver international experience and evidence-based therapies to Georgia:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>To develop successful models of education, inclusion, and social adaptation based on best practices and guided by the best international experts; to prove their efficiency through documented results and subsequently replicate pilot experiments for across Georgia (see &laquo;<a href="https://www.autism.ge/resursnyj-klass" target="_blank">Resource Class</a>&raquo; project);</li>\n<li>To develop and publish information (print and digital) accessible to anyone interested in understanding autism and the ways to manage it, simultaneously training and preparing local high level professional personnel;</li>\n<li>To introduce internationally-recognized methods and therapies to manage autism in Georgia (see &laquo;<a href="https://www.autism.ge/alternativnye-kommunikacii-pecs" target="_blank">PECS &ndash; Picture Exchange Communication System</a>&raquo; project)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol start="3">\n<li>To create &ldquo;a friendly environment&rdquo; for ASD people in Georgia:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>To develop infrastructure to accommodate social activities for ASD children and adults by adapting cinemas, theatres, concert halls, restaurants and other social venues for their visits (see &ldquo;<a href="https://www.autism.ge/druzhelyubnaya-sreda" target="_blank">Friendly Environment</a>&rdquo; project);</li>\n<li>To organize educational workshops among the population, particularly in rural regions; aiding teachers, doctors, and priests to better understand autism and its treatment (see &ldquo;<a href="http://www.autism.ge" target="_blank">Pastor&rsquo;s Psychology</a>&rdquo; project);</li>\n<li>To fight for changes in Georgian legislation to support the rights of ASD children and adults and to encourage the state&rsquo;s support for charitable activities.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, 0, 'charityautism', NULL, 1, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL),
